It is hardly likely that a different state of things would prevail at the place indicated above, that is Gindale, and the inference is that the ofnams named in these Rievaulx deeds were simply ‘ i11taks,’ or enclosures from the common made by the lord himself. One other consideration may tend to establish this view. The whole of the Cleveland district, with only small exceptions, was not only occupied, but named (or re-named, perhaps) by the Danes and Northmen, and, as might be expected, the dialect-words of the district are Scandinavian to a very remarkable extent indeed.
